    "image_with_text_t6KzFw": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CcwiLn": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p>From comic books and Saturday morning cartoons to global design collaborations, <a href=\"https://chairmanting.com/featured\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://chairmanting.com/featured\">Carson Ting</a> has always been drawn to expressive imagery. Growing up in Toronto and now based in Vancouver, he has built a practice that moves fluidly between illustration, design, and fine art. We spoke with Carson about early inspirations, creative routines, and the beloved family pet that sparked his <a href=\"https://www.billionbuns.com/\" target=\"_blank\" title=\"https://www.billionbuns.com/\">Billion Buns</a> universe.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CcwiLn"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/IMG_6201.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "layout": "image_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "middle",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "scheme-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 36,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_wKVLmh": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_CLbqn8": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q:</strong> What are 3 words your friends and family would use to describe you? </p><p><strong>A: </strong>Driven, curious, and dependable.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_CLbqn8"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/IMG_6179.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "layout": "text_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "middle",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "scheme-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 0,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_Xcm763": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_MVB6xn": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q:</strong> Did you grow up surrounded by art, or did you go looking for it? </p><p><strong>A: </strong>Yes, but not by design. We always had a good mix of Western and Eastern comic books. These ranged from Archie, DC, and Marvel to Hong Kong classics like Old Master Q (<em>Lo Fu Zhi</em>, IYKYK). Between the comic books and Saturday morning cartoons like <em>Bugs Bunny</em> and my all-time favourite, <em>Fables of the Green Forest</em>, I was incredibly inspired by all the art in my orbit.</p><p>Growing up in Toronto, my dad started his own independent Chinese Canadian newspaper in our basement. I remember seeing all the typesetting machinery, and that visual really etched itself into my memory. But the most pivotal moment was when my dad first introduced me to pencil crayons. It truly blew my mind. I thought pencils only produced grey lines, so when I saw that these produced colour on paper, I was completely floored.</p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_MVB6xn"
      ],
      "settings": {
        "image": "shopify://shop_images/IMG_6244.jpg",
        "height": "adapt",
        "desktop_image_width": "medium",
        "layout": "image_first",
        "desktop_content_position": "middle",
        "desktop_content_alignment": "left",
        "content_layout": "no-overlap",
        "color_scheme": "scheme-1",
        "mobile_content_alignment": "left",
        "padding_top": 0,
        "padding_bottom": 36
      }
    },
    "image_with_text_qim38J": {
      "type": "image-with-text",
      "blocks": {
        "text_gGCMN3": {
          "type": "text",
          "settings": {
            "text": "<p><strong>Q: </strong>How did the creative energy in Toronto shape your early work, compared to the Vancouver scene now? </p><p><strong>A:</strong> Toronto taught me pace and pressure. It is a city that pushes you to perform, compete, and work fast. Toronto gave me the gift of grit through the grind, and it was a great place for training.</p><p>On the other side of the spectrum, Vancouver is more reflective. It gives me space to think about the meaning of my work. I think if I hadn’t cut my teeth in advertising art direction in Toronto, I wouldn’t have the same level of discipline and focus in Vancouver.</p><p></p><p></p>",
            "text_style": "body"
          }
        }
      },
      "block_order": [
        "text_gGCMN3"
      ],
